vote <- read.csv('voteincome.csv')
# Your answers here

The dataset has the following informations:

  • VoteIncome:

Sample Turnout and Demographic Data from the 2000 Current Population Survey

This data set contains turnout and demographic data from a sample of respondents to the 2000 Current Population Survey (CPS). The states represented are South Carolina and Arkansas. The data represent only a sample and results from this example should not be used in publication.

Format A data frame containing 7 variables (“state”, “year”, “vote”, “income”, “education”, “age”, “female”) and 1500 observations.

vote an integer vector taking on values “1” (Voted) and “0” (Did Not Vote)

income an integer vector ranging from “4” (Less than $5000) to “17” (Greater than $75000) denoting family income. See the CPS codebook for more information on variable coding

education an integer vector ranging from “1” (Less than High School Education) to “4” (More than a College Education). See the CPS codebook for more information on variable coding

References https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/cps.html

2 (2 pt). Make a boxplot (or violin-plot) of income, segmented by education. What can you infer from this plot?

vote  %>%ggplot() +geom_boxplot (mapping = aes(x = as.factor(education), y = income))

# Your answers here

From the boxplot, it seems to be that the higher education one has, the higher the median of income there is.

3 (2 pt). Are more educated people more likely to vote? Check that by making a mosaic-plot of vote against education.

ggplot(data = vote) +geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = factor(vote),fill = as.factor(education)),position = 'fill')

# Your answers here

More educated people are more likely to vote. Looking at the mosaic plot, (0 being people do not vote and 1 meaning people do vote) more educated people tended to vote more (4 and 3 are larger in 1 than 0) and more people with 1 and 2 education did not vote than did

4 (2 pt). Make a barplot of the variable education. Plot each bar using a different color.

ggplot(data = vote) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=factor(education)), fill =rainbow(4), color = 'black')

5 (2 pt). Make a plot to answer the following question: is there a relation between age and income? (Hint: the plot is going to look ugly. Add a trend line to see the relationship.)

ggplot(data = vote) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=age, y=income))+geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=age, y=income), method= 'lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# Your answers here

There seems to be a negative correlation between age in income. There is a downward trendline, and it it shows that the older you are, the lower your income is
